Original Text: For 64-bit jvms, as per [OA24232](http://m.ibm.com/http/publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/zidocms2/72.1?SHELF=ZDOCAPAR&DT=20120831070418&wirelessshow=1), we use &DS to tell the IEATDUMP to auto-allocate datasets which have &DS in the name pattern.
Processed Text: For 64-bit jvms, as per [OA24232](http://m.ibm.com/http/publibz.boulder.ibm.com/cgi-bin/bookmgr_OS390/BOOKS/zidocms2/72.1?SHELF=ZDOCAPAR&DT=20120831070418&wirelessshow=1), we use &DS to tell the IEATDUMP to auto-allocate datasets which have &DS in the name pattern.

Original Text: It's unlikely that the duplicate dataset name could be caused by the IEATDUMP routine failing to correctly increment the &DS suffix.
Processed Text: It's unlikely that the duplicate dataset name could be caused by the IEATDUMP routine failing to correctly increment the &DS suffix.

Original Text: Update: the cause of the NullPointerException seems to be a bug in Monitor Elimination.
Processed Text: Update: the cause of the NullPointerException seems to be a bug in Monitor Elimination.

Original Text: Monitor Elimination manipulates the catch blocks and exception edges created by this CFG Simplification pattern.
Processed Text: Monitor Elimination manipulates the catch blocks and exception edges created by this CFG Simplification pattern.

Original Text:
Here, monitor elimination tries to add a new exception edge from the NULLCHK block created by CFG simplification to a new catch block created by monitor elimination:
https://github.com/eclipse/openj9/blob/fc545f28f0aba766cca8f78f37d5e4fb9a2f1f4d/runtime/compiler/optimizer/MonitorElimination.cpp#L4529

Then, monitor elimination removes the old exception edge:
https://github.com/eclipse/openj9/blob/fc545f28f0aba766cca8f78f37d5e4fb9a2f1f4d/runtime/compiler/optimizer/MonitorElimination.cpp#L4541
Processed Text:
Here, monitor elimination tries to add a new exception edge from the NULLCHK block created by CFG simplification to a new catch block created by monitor elimination:
https://github.com/eclipse/openj9/blob/fc545f28f0aba766cca8f78f37d5e4fb9a2f1f4d/runtime/compiler/optimizer/MonitorElimination.cpp#L4529

Then, monitor elimination removes the old exception edge:
https://github.com/eclipse/openj9/blob/fc545f28f0aba766cca8f78f37d5e4fb9a2f1f4d/runtime/compiler/optimizer/MonitorElimination.cpp#L4541

Original Text:
The problem is that CODE silently fails to add a new exception edge if there is an existing edge that catches the same exceptions:
https://github.com/eclipse/omr/blob/b99d3036d8a20592a04fdcd77bca176e794e326d/compiler/infra/OMRCfg.cpp#L202-L211

This leaves the NULLCHK node created by CFG simplification without any exception edge to a catch block.
Processed Text:
The problem is that CODE silently fails to add a new exception edge if there is an existing edge that catches the same exceptions:
https://github.com/eclipse/omr/blob/b99d3036d8a20592a04fdcd77bca176e794e326d/compiler/infra/OMRCfg.cpp#L202-L211

This leaves the NULLCHK node created by CFG simplification without any exception edge to a catch block.

Original Text: Thus, when the NULLCHK fails, an uncaught NullPointerException is thrown.
Processed Text: Thus, when the NULLCHK fails, an uncaught NullPointerException is thrown.

Original Text: I have opened https://github.com/eclipse/omr/pull/5406 to create a new OMR CFG method which will add an exception edge even when there is an existing one.
Processed Text: I have opened https://github.com/eclipse/omr/pull/5406 to create a new OMR CFG method which will add an exception edge even when there is an existing one.

Processed Text: Introduce notion of recognized classes for JIT

Original Text: The JIT in OpenJ9 has a notion of recognized methods that are used to check for particular methods.
Processed Text: The JIT in OpenJ9 has a notion of recognized methods that are used to check for particular methods.

Original Text: It also has ways of checking for a group of related methods (e.g., CODE).
Processed Text: It also has ways of checking for a group of related methods (e.g., CODE).

Original Text: Having a similar way of tracking recognized classes and groups of related classes would be handy.
Processed Text: Having a similar way of tracking recognized classes and groups of related classes would be handy.

Original Text: Today, classes are recognized by performing CODE and CODE on their names or parts of their names, which is clumsy and can result in obscure coding errors.
Processed Text: Today, classes are recognized by performing CODE and CODE on their names or parts of their names, which is clumsy and can result in obscure coding errors.

Original Text: When JVM is processing a class file, it should follow this order: loading, linking, and initializing.

Original Text: NoClassDefFoundError is thrown at the loading stage, and VerifyError is thrown at the linking stage (verification happens during linking).

Original Text:
### TL;DR

Improve AWT support to use dynamic linking of the AWT native code libraries.
Processed Text:
### TL;DR

Improve AWT support to use dynamic linking of the AWT native code libraries.

Original Text: Generalize the dynamic linking approach, which is currently used only on Windows, to all platforms.
Processed Text: Generalize the dynamic linking approach, which is currently used only on Windows, to all platforms.

Original Text:
Drop the current static linking approach used for Linux

### Goals

The current support for AWT on Windows uses dynamic linking of the native code libraries: the unmodified shared libraries of the JDK are loaded dynamically at image run time using the regular JNI mechanism.
Processed Text:
Drop the current static linking approach used for Linux

### Goals

The current support for AWT on Windows uses dynamic linking of the native code libraries: the unmodified shared libraries of the JDK are loaded dynamically at image run time using the regular JNI mechanism.

Original Text: The only "downside" of this approach is that the shared libraries need to be shipped together with the application executable.
Processed Text: The only "downside" of this approach is that the shared libraries need to be shipped together with the application executable.

Original Text: On Linux, currently a static linking approach is used: the AWT native code is linked statically into the application.
Processed Text: On Linux, currently a static linking approach is used: the AWT native code is linked statically into the application.

Original Text: This approach has significant compatibility issues and would require changes to the native code for future JDK versions and to support additional platforms.
Processed Text: This approach has significant compatibility issues and would require changes to the native code for future JDK versions and to support additional platforms.

Original Text: It is therefore a goal to remove the static linking approach on Linux and switch to the dynamic linking.
Processed Text: It is therefore a goal to remove the static linking approach on Linux and switch to the dynamic linking.

Original Text: Once dynamic linking is working on Windows and Linux, adding support for MacOS will be not much additional work.
Processed Text: Once dynamic linking is working on Windows and Linux, adding support for MacOS will be not much additional work.

Original Text: ### Non
Processed Text: ### Non

Processed Text: -goals

Original Text: We will remove the current static linking approach used for Linux.
Processed Text: We will remove the current static linking approach used for Linux.

Original Text: This approach can be considered a failed experiment because it is not maintainable and has no significant benefits over the dynamic linking approach.
Processed Text: This approach can be considered a failed experiment because it is not maintainable and has no significant benefits over the dynamic linking approach.

Processed Text: * It is not a goal to provide a complete reflection and resource registration of all parts of AWT.

Original Text: I used a [wine patch by Zebediah Figura](https://bugs.winehq.org/show_bug.cgi?id=46633) and added some code on top of it to get the Win32 threadpool IO-related callbacks to work in wine, and then wine-mono also complained about null references in this managed callback.

Original Text: Understanding WAMR AoT formats
Processed Text: Understanding WAMR AoT formats

Original Text: The AoT compiler can generate code that can run really fast.
Processed Text: The AoT compiler can generate code that can run really fast.

Original Text: However there are multiple formats that the compiler can output.
Processed Text: However there are multiple formats that the compiler can output.

Original Text: The formats are aot, object, llvmir-unopt and llvmir-opt.
Processed Text: The formats are aot, object, llvmir-unopt and llvmir-opt.

Original Text: AoT doesnt necessarily mean compiling to native code.
Processed Text: AoT doesnt necessarily mean compiling to native code.

Original Text: Is it right to assume that the CODE format is optimized intermediate representation that WAMR can use, not native code?
Processed Text: Is it right to assume that the CODE format is optimized intermediate representation that WAMR can use, not native code?

Original Text: @Rochet2 currently the other three formats are for debug purpose only, iwasm cannot load and run them.
Processed Text: @Rochet2 currently the other three formats are for debug purpose only, iwasm cannot load and run them.

Original Text: The aot format is refactored from the object file: WASM bytecode -> LLVM IR -> object file -> aot file.
Processed Text: The aot format is refactored from the object file: WASM bytecode -> LLVM IR -> object file -> aot file.

Original Text: We extract the necessary data from object file, e.g. native code, relocation info, and extract the init data from wasm file, and then merge/re-org these data together to generate aot file.
Processed Text: We extract the necessary data from object file, e.g. native code, relocation info, and extract the init data from wasm file, and then merge/re-org these data together to generate aot file.

Original Text: Is the native code able to break the sandbox?
Processed Text: Is the native code able to break the sandbox?

Original Text:
For example, would it be able to edit the runtime or other modules run with the same runtime as they run in the same process?
Or are the function calls and memory access checked by the runtime prior/during run-time?
Processed Text:
For example, would it be able to edit the runtime or other modules run with the same runtime as they run in the same process?
Or are the function calls and memory access checked by the runtime prior/during run-time?

Original Text: I am not talking about hypothetical breaches in the sandbox due to programming errors or similar, just trying to figure out if there is any checking at all.
Processed Text: I am not talking about hypothetical breaches in the sandbox due to programming errors or similar, just trying to figure out if there is any checking at all.

Original Text: Yes, the similar sandbox checks in interpreter are also applied in AoT native code, e.g. memory access boundary check, integer divide by zero check, call unlinked function check, stack overflow check and so on.
Processed Text: Yes, the similar sandbox checks in interpreter are also applied in AoT native code, e.g. memory access boundary check, integer divide by zero check, call unlinked function check, stack overflow check and so on.

Original Text: And the section content size is encoded using [LEB128](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LEB128), with byte count no larger than (bitwidth + 6)/7, (e.g. u32, max byte count is (32+6)/7) = 5), and if a byte's highest bit is 1, there is next byte, otherwise it is the last byte.

Processed Text: Cranelift aarch64 backend: use constant pool to defer constant emission to the end, unless out of range

Original Text: Currently, to avoid issues with (i) the PC-relative addressing range of CODE, and (ii) the fact that the constant pool needs to be relocatable, the aarch64 backend emits constants inline with code and branches around them.
Processed Text: Currently, to avoid issues with (i) the PC-relative addressing range of CODE, and (ii) the fact that the constant pool needs to be relocatable, the aarch64 backend emits constants inline with code and branches around them.

Original Text: This is obviously suboptimal for code-density and branchiness reasons.
Processed Text: This is obviously suboptimal for code-density and branchiness reasons.

Original Text: To handle the first issue, we should use the CODE to collect constants, as the old backend does, and then modify our emission logic to defer constant emission to the end *unless* we're about to go out of range of pending constant references, in which case we emit a "constant island".
Processed Text: To handle the first issue, we should use the CODE to collect constants, as the old backend does, and then modify our emission logic to defer constant emission to the end *unless* we're about to go out of range of pending constant references, in which case we emit a "constant island".

Original Text: To handle the second issue, we need to emit constant-pool relocations.
Processed Text: To handle the second issue, we need to emit constant-pool relocations.

Original Text: It's still unclear how we can handle the intersection of these two, i.e., when constant references become out-of-range because the client relocates the constant pool further away.
Processed Text: It's still unclear how we can handle the intersection of these two, i.e., when constant references become out-of-range because the client relocates the constant pool further away.

Original Text: One known use case of the relocatable constant pool is for SpiderMonkey to insert its own epilogue into Wasm functions; there, at least, we can bound how much further away the constant pool will be, so perhaps we can just have a slightly-conservative limit for when we must emit a constant island.

Original Text: Cranelift: ARM32 backend: active maintenance, or remove?
Processed Text: Cranelift: ARM32 backend: active maintenance, or remove?

Original Text: In the [Cranelift biweekly](https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/blob/main/meetings/cranelift/2022/cranelift-01-24.md) today, we discussed the ARM32 backend and how to handle it with respect to our ISLE transition, and maintenance / breaking changes in internal APIs in general.
Processed Text: In the [Cranelift biweekly](https://github.com/bytecodealliance/wasmtime/blob/main/meetings/cranelift/2022/cranelift-01-24.md) today, we discussed the ARM32 backend and how to handle it with respect to our ISLE transition, and maintenance / breaking changes in internal APIs in general.

Original Text: The current state of the ARM32 backend is incomplete: it supports 32-bit code, but panics on any 64-bit operation, so it does not yet support (for example) Wasm-MVP with the CODE frontend, nor would it support most code generated by CODE.
Processed Text: The current state of the ARM32 backend is incomplete: it supports 32-bit code, but panics on any 64-bit operation, so it does not yet support (for example) Wasm-MVP with the CODE frontend, nor would it support most code generated by CODE.

Original Text: The intent when merging the partial backend was to allow it to mature in-tree with further contributions.
Processed Text: The intent when merging the partial backend was to allow it to mature in-tree with further contributions.

Original Text: However, that hasn't materialized in the year or so since merging.
Processed Text: However, that hasn't materialized in the year or so since merging.

Original Text: We have made changes as needed to keep it compiling, but there is a larger question of what happens to an incomplete backend with no active maintainers or users, especially if it implies more significant amounts of work.
Processed Text: We have made changes as needed to keep it compiling, but there is a larger question of what happens to an incomplete backend with no active maintainers or users, especially if it implies more significant amounts of work.

Original Text: With our ISLE DSL transition, we would need to invest nontrivial time to move the backend over; and the upcoming regalloc2 transition would require more effort as well.
Processed Text: With our ISLE DSL transition, we would need to invest nontrivial time to move the backend over; and the upcoming regalloc2 transition would require more effort as well.

Original Text: It seems reasonable to ask: if the backend is incomplete, and no one is using or maintaining it, should we remove it instead?
Processed Text: It seems reasonable to ask: if the backend is incomplete, and no one is using or maintaining it, should we remove it instead?

Original Text: Consensus in our meeting today was that this seems reasonable.
Processed Text: Consensus in our meeting today was that this seems reasonable.

Original Text: However, if anyone would like to work toward a usable and maintained ARM32 backend, now is the time to step forward!
Processed Text: However, if anyone would like to work toward a usable and maintained ARM32 backend, now is the time to step forward!

Original Text: Thoughts?
Processed Text: Thoughts?

Original Text: Hi @cfallin, I understand the situation you and the maintainers are in.
Processed Text: Hi @cfallin, I understand the situation you and the maintainers are in.

Original Text: We are not currently a user of wasmtime/cranelift on arm32
Processed Text: We are not currently a user of wasmtime/cranelift on arm32

Original Text: but we have been evaluating projects to potentially target wasm via wasmtime on our fleet of IoT hubs.
Processed Text: but we have been evaluating projects to potentially target wasm via wasmtime on our fleet of IoT hubs.

Original Text: To consider use of wasmtime/cranelift, arm32 support is a must as we continue to support software updates for a very large number of products using arm32 (in addition to products based on aarch64/x86_64/etc.) and would guess that this is true for other potential users in this space.
Processed Text: To consider use of wasmtime/cranelift, arm32 support is a must as we continue to support software updates for a very large number of products using arm32 (in addition to products based on aarch64/x86_64/etc.) and would guess that this is true for other potential users in this space.

Original Text: Thus far, one of the reasons we have not yet built solutions around wasm is the lack of arm32 support which we had hoped would be something that would get love from ARM or others.
Processed Text: Thus far, one of the reasons we have not yet built solutions around wasm is the lack of arm32 support which we had hoped would be something that would get love from ARM or others.

Original Text: I will reach out to some of my contacts within the broader Samsung org to see if we are currently in a position to provide any assistance; I do feel that if IoT is in fact an area where we would like wasmtime/cranelift to be applicable along with the goal of providing a portable bytecode that arm32 support is a critical feature.
Processed Text: I will reach out to some of my contacts within the broader Samsung org to see if we are currently in a position to provide any assistance; I do feel that if IoT is in fact an area where we would like wasmtime/cranelift to be applicable along with the goal of providing a portable bytecode that arm32 support is a critical feature.

Original Text:
**
CODE is a black hole - it can't be converted to/from without ugly hacks which makes interop with other parts of the ecosystem painful.

**
CODE is a black hole - it can't be converted to/from without ugly hacks which makes interop with other parts of the ecosystem painful.

Original Text:
**Describe the solution you'd like**
I'd like to have a clear way to use, for instance, chrono::DateTime with CODE.
Processed Text:
**Describe the solution you'd like**
I'd like to have a clear way to use, for instance, chrono::DateTime with CODE.

Original Text: I'm not sure how this could be implemented.
Processed Text: I'm not sure how this could be implemented.

Original Text: A way to get an instant from a unix timestamp could be good enough, but this would probably require Tokio's Instant to not just wrap CODE.
Processed Text: A way to get an instant from a unix timestamp could be good enough, but this would probably require Tokio's Instant to not just wrap CODE.

Original Text: Or maybe removing Instant/sleep_until/DelayQueue from CODE would be better?
Processed Text: Or maybe removing Instant/sleep_until/DelayQueue from CODE would be better?

Original Text: An external implementation could rely on chrono or whatever without worrying about increasing CODE's dependencies.
Processed Text: An external implementation could rely on chrono or whatever without worrying about increasing CODE's dependencies.

Original Text:

Processed Text:
**Describe alternatives you've considered**

Original Text: The issues are extra CODE calls, hidden dependency on the clock, and imprecision due to the clock advancing between now calls.
Processed Text: The issues are extra CODE calls, hidden dependency on the clock, and imprecision due to the clock advancing between now calls.

Original Text: The CODE type is useful because changing the system clock doesn't affect the CODE type.
Processed Text: The CODE type is useful because changing the system clock doesn't affect the CODE type.

Original Text: Supporting unix timestamps or chrono types requires being able to detect when the system time is changed forward or backwards or just repeatedly sleeping for a short time and checking the system time again.
Processed Text: Supporting unix timestamps or chrono types requires being able to detect when the system time is changed forward or backwards or just repeatedly sleeping for a short time and checking the system time again.

Original Text: I think stating limitations up front, such as not handling system time changes if something other than Instant is used, would be fine.
Processed Text: I think stating limitations up front, such as not handling system time changes if something other than Instant is used, would be fine.

Original Text: But I don't think it's necessary to deal with that or store any other types within the sleep struct.

Original Text:
gRPC: https://github.com/grpc/grpc-go/blob/master/codes/codes.go#L195
http: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_HTTP_status_codes

The incoming and outgoing traffic is exchanged on the protocol, because Dapr provides a standard API, so the protocol  is common, but there is no standard to support the exchange of response status code.
Processed Text:
gRPC: https://github.com/grpc/grpc-go/blob/master/codes/codes.go#L195

The incoming and outgoing traffic is exchanged on the protocol, because Dapr provides a standard API, so the protocol  is common, but there is no standard to support the exchange of response status code.

The problem this brings is:

The HTTP 200 return code, obtained by other RPC and gRPC, may become a response error.

Processed Text: The minimum HTTP response code starts with 1xx; so there is no intersection according to the response code interval, so it is easy to handle.

Original Text: If the user enables this feature (probably should be off by default) e.g. via an environment variable, whenever we compile a module, we produce the code cache for the module, and on process exit, we store any new cache produced in a cache directory on the file system.
Processed Text: If the user enables this feature (probably should be off by default) e.g. via an environment variable, whenever we compile a module, we produce the code cache for the module, and on process exit, we store any new cache produced in a cache directory on the file system.

Original Text: The next time the process is launched (with this feature enabled again), whenever we are loading a module, we attempt to load the cache from that directory and use it when compiling the module, in order to speed up the start up (where most of the time is usually spent on compilation).
Processed Text: The next time the process is launched (with this feature enabled again), whenever we are loading a module, we attempt to load the cache from that directory and use it when compiling the module, in order to speed up the start up (where most of the time is usually spent on compilation).

Original Text: This is also similar to [what Chrome does with the V8 code cache](https://v8.dev/blog/code-caching-for-devs).
Processed Text: This is also similar to [what Chrome does with the V8 code cache](https://v8.dev/blog/code-caching-for-devs).

Original Text: The motivation for implementing this in core is that, for a user-land module to do this for CJS, it has to monkey patch the CJS loader, and this increases the compatibility burden (v8-compile-cache [has 17M weekly downloads](https://www.npmjs.com/package/v8-compile-cache), and it needs to monkey-patch CODE to work.
Processed Text: The motivation for implementing this in core is that, for a user-land module to do this for CJS, it has to monkey patch the CJS loader, and this increases the compatibility burden (v8-compile-cache [has 17M weekly downloads](https://www.npmjs.com/package/v8-compile-cache), and it needs to monkey-patch CODE to work.

Original Text: I think this issue might affect a lot of use cases because it comes into play any time we take something that is 'actually' async like reading chunks from a file system or the network and then amplify it synchronously in any way, such as decompression, parsing strings into structured objects (xml, json, ...), collecting certain keywords, etc.. It does not feel like something users would write themselves a lot, but lower level libraries probably will and users will end up just thinking for-await-of is slow, I have to go back to writing stream handlers myself, thereby missing out on the control flow improvements of for-await-of (such as using await in the loop block, i.e. delaying the next iteration until the completion of something async).
Processed Text: I think this issue might affect a lot of use cases because it comes into play any time we take something that is 'actually' async like reading chunks from a file system or the network and then amplify it synchronously in any way, such as decompression, parsing strings into structured objects (xml, json, ...), collecting certain keywords, etc.. It does not feel like something users would write themselves a lot, but lower level libraries probably will and users will end up just thinking for-await-of is slow, I have to go back to writing stream handlers myself, thereby missing out on the control flow improvements of for-await-of (such as using await in the loop block, i.e. delaying the next iteration until the completion of something async).

Original Text: Feature Request: Support handling more histograms in MetricsEventSource
Processed Text: Feature Request: Support handling more histograms in MetricsEventSource

Original Text: Currently MetricsEventSource has a default of limit of I think 100 histograms that it will track because each one uses a non-trivial amount of memory.
Processed Text: Currently MetricsEventSource has a default of limit of I think 100 histograms that it will track because each one uses a non-trivial amount of memory.

Original Text: We are starting to see use cases that are likely to easily exhaust those limits such as the duration counters added in https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/47536.
Processed Text: We are starting to see use cases that are likely to easily exhaust those limits such as the duration counters added in https://github.com/dotnet/aspnetcore/issues/47536.

Original Text: The limit is adjustable so a brute force approach is simply to raise the limit and use a bunch of memory but that probably isn't a great option.
Processed Text: The limit is adjustable so a brute force approach is simply to raise the limit and use a bunch of memory but that probably isn't a great option.

Original Text:
In order to make tools built on top of MetricsEventSource be more effective we probably need to improve this by doing one of:
- Creating options to track more histograms using less memory for each.
Processed Text:
In order to make tools built on top of MetricsEventSource be more effective we probably need to improve this by doing one of:
- Creating options to track more histograms using less memory for each.

Original Text: We could do this by some combination of reducing accuracy or increasing CPU usage per measurement to use a more memory efficient data storage.
Processed Text: We could do this by some combination of reducing accuracy or increasing CPU usage per measurement to use a more memory efficient data storage.

Original Text:
- Creating options that let tools be more precise about which attribute values they want to track
- Creating options that let tools request that some attribute values be elided so there will be fewer total histograms produced.
Processed Text:
- Creating options that let tools be more precise about which attribute values they want to track
- Creating options that let tools request that some attribute values be elided so there will be fewer total histograms produced.

Original Text: What is the 100 limit for - is it histogram buckets, or the combination of dimension values?
Processed Text: What is the 100 limit for - is it histogram buckets, or the combination of dimension values?

Original Text: And is this per Histogram or is this across all the histograms?
Processed Text: And is this per Histogram or is this across all the histograms?

Original Text:
What is the 100 limit for 

It is a limit on the number histogram time-series that will be reported by MetricsEventSource by default.
Processed Text:
What is the 100 limit for 

It is a limit on the number histogram time-series that will be reported by MetricsEventSource by default.

Original Text: Each unique combination of a Histogram instrument + the unordered set of tag name-value pairs generates a unique time-series.
Processed Text: Each unique combination of a Histogram instrument + the unordered set of tag name-value pairs generates a unique time-series.

Original Text: Out of those the subscriber to MetricsEventSource may have only requested that certain instruments be tracked so only combinations using those instruments will be reported on.
Processed Text: Out of those the subscriber to MetricsEventSource may have only requested that certain instruments be tracked so only combinations using those instruments will be reported on.

Original Text:
As a hypothetical example:

CODE

If the MetricsEventSource subscriber requests to track meter "A" then there will be 4 time-series reported counting against that limit:
histogram a, color=blue, size=big
histogram a, color=red, size=big
histogram a, color=red
histogram a2, color=red

By default after 100 different combinations have been observed future combinations will not be reported.

Original Text: Normally this field is already CODE but when the application is started by the CPU profiler it is set to CODE.
Processed Text: Normally this field is already CODE but when the application is started by the CPU profiler it is set to CODE.

Original Text: By reverting it back to CODE we disable the costly and unwanted ETW event tracing and get a representative CPU profile without slowing down the application.
Processed Text: By reverting it back to CODE we disable the costly and unwanted ETW event tracing and get a representative CPU profile without slowing down the application.

Original Text: This won't help when *attaching* a CPU profiler to a running process.
Processed Text: This won't help when *attaching* a CPU profiler to a running process.

Original Text: This can be worked around by starting a thread within the application to periodically set CODE to CODE.
Processed Text: This can be worked around by starting a thread within the application to periodically set CODE to CODE.

Original Text:
I was able to repro on net6 and net7-rc2 on Windows, Ryzen 9 5900HS in POH mode (only); I was ultimately unable to make any significant inroads into what was actually happening, other than "bad things"

I tried a few scenarios:

- as-written: fails after a while with NRE in CODE
- using the indexer-setter on the dictionary CODE - fails (after more iterations, but often less time - indexer is much faster) with an assertion error on the value - typically seeing values like CODE where the zero was expected
- using the alternative overload CODE - again much faster, but fails eventually

It certainly *feels* like a GC tracking error that is specific to POH reachability checks for values only reachable by interior managed pointers; however - multiple *simpler* scenarios that targeted exactly that: did nothing interesting and worked as expected.

**Events:**
- ConnectionStarted - Triggered when a connection is established.
- ConnectionEnded - Triggered when a connection is terminated gracefully.

- FrameSent - Triggered when an frame is sent from the server.
- FrameReceived - Triggered when an frame is received by the server.

Original Text: ConditionalWeakTable memory leak
Processed Text: ConditionalWeakTable memory leak

Original Text: I reviewed the source code for ConditionalWeakTable, particularly [Remove](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/mscorlib/src/System/Runtime/CompilerServices/ConditionalWeakTable.cs#L161) method and [Resize](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/mscorlib/src/System/Runtime/CompilerServices/ConditionalWeakTable.cs#L483).
Processed Text: I reviewed the source code for ConditionalWeakTable, particularly [Remove](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/mscorlib/src/System/Runtime/CompilerServices/ConditionalWeakTable.cs#L161) method and [Resize](https://github.com/dotnet/coreclr/blob/master/src/mscorlib/src/System/Runtime/CompilerServices/ConditionalWeakTable.cs#L483).

Original Text: The "Resize" method used for internal data structure maintenance NEVER shrinks internal arrays (namely "_buckets" and "_entries"), they can only grow in length.
Processed Text: The "Resize" method used for internal data structure maintenance NEVER shrinks internal arrays (namely "_buckets" and "_entries"), they can only grow in length.

Original Text: On x64, one ConditionalWeakTable entry takes roughly 40 bytes.
Processed Text: On x64, one ConditionalWeakTable entry takes roughly 40 bytes.

Original Text: Thus, if I use ConditionalWeakTable to bind one million objects, then let them all get garbage collected, the internal arrays still remain allocated (.Length = 1 000 000) and in effect I leak about 40 MB of uncollectable space.
Processed Text: Thus, if I use ConditionalWeakTable to bind one million objects, then let them all get garbage collected, the internal arrays still remain allocated (.Length = 1 000 000) and in effect I leak about 40 MB of uncollectable space.

Original Text: The only solution now is to monitor how many active/dead items are in the table, and periodically recreate the whole table (and rebind all live entries) when some threshold is reached.
Processed Text: The only solution now is to monitor how many active/dead items are in the table, and periodically recreate the whole table (and rebind all live entries) when some threshold is reached.

Original Text: "Remove" works similarly, it only marks removed items as "free", but does not allow for the space to be actually reclaimed (only reused).
Processed Text: "Remove" works similarly, it only marks removed items as "free", but does not allow for the space to be actually reclaimed (only reused).

Original Text: Thanks for the report.
Processed Text: Thanks for the report.

Original Text: @AlexGhiondea can you get this routed appropriately?
Processed Text: @AlexGhiondea can you get this routed appropriately?

Original Text: Furthermore, because of how **DependentHandle** works, the **ConditionalWeakTable** unfortunately can't automatically reclaim the space once a _primary target_ gets collected, because there is simply no _event_ to hook up to get notified.
Processed Text: Furthermore, because of how **DependentHandle** works, the **ConditionalWeakTable** unfortunately can't automatically reclaim the space once a _primary target_ gets collected, because there is simply no _event_ to hook up to get notified.

Original Text: I guess it would be nice to have a new public method on **ConditionalWeakTable** called _Reclaim_ that would allow the user code to instruct the weak table to shrink.
Processed Text: I guess it would be nice to have a new public method on **ConditionalWeakTable** called _Reclaim_ that would allow the user code to instruct the weak table to shrink.

Original Text: As far as I know, the only way to implement automatic reclamation when _primary targets_ get collected is using finalizers, but I believe that would hurt the performance too much as a general solution.
Processed Text: As far as I know, the only way to implement automatic reclamation when _primary targets_ get collected is using finalizers, but I believe that would hurt the performance too much as a general solution.

Original Text: I would leave that to the user code to implement if need be, which could call the _Reclaim_ at appropriate times.
Processed Text: I would leave that to the user code to implement if need be, which could call the _Reclaim_ at appropriate times.

Original Text: I can see how the Reclaim method could help in certain scenarios.
Processed Text: I can see how the Reclaim method could help in certain scenarios.

Original Text: However, I also think that it would be very similar to blowing away the table and starting again - which can be achieved from user code just as you have pointed out.
Processed Text: However, I also think that it would be very similar to blowing away the table and starting again - which can be achieved from user code just as you have pointed out.

Original Text: It I remember correctly (and I might be wrong :smile:) , the pattern of only growing the internal arrays is something we have in all of our collections.
Processed Text: It I remember correctly (and I might be wrong :smile:) , the pattern of only growing the internal arrays is something we have in all of our collections.

Original Text: CODEs are immutable; if you change the value of an CODE; it creates a new CODE and replaces the current one with that.
Processed Text: CODEs are immutable; if you change the value of an CODE; it creates a new CODE and replaces the current one with that.

Original Text: That new CODE will be used by everything that completes sync and captured in any async method that suspends and resumes later after that point (mimicking the sync behaviour).
Processed Text: That new CODE will be used by everything that completes sync and captured in any async method that suspends and resumes later after that point (mimicking the sync behaviour).

Original Text: However; when completion of the current async method causes a previous async method to resume, that async method will have captured an earlier CODE with an earlier CODE value prior to the change.
Processed Text: However; when completion of the current async method causes a previous async method to resume, that async method will have captured an earlier CODE with an earlier CODE value prior to the change.

Original Text: So while CODEs flow; they also unwind their values like a stack as the async methods stack unwinds.
Processed Text: So while CODEs flow; they also unwind their values like a stack as the async methods stack unwinds.
